# Who may publish what.
#
# The engine is the only party permitted to write econ/commands/#. Nodes report and
# listen; they do not command each other. This is what stops one compromised ceiling box
# from switching every relay on the floor — authentication alone would not.

# The Go engine: reads all telemetry and status, issues all commands.
user econ-engine
topic read econ/telemetry/#
topic read econ/status/#
topic write econ/commands/#

# Edge nodes (ESP32, Pico, Raspberry Pi gateway, CV occupancy nodes) share this identity.
# They publish their own telemetry and liveness, and subscribe to commands.
#
# Per-node identities are the next step and are the right answer for a real install: give
# every board its own user and narrow these wildcards to its own topic. That work is
# gated on provisioning (see ROADMAP: firmware identity is baked into build flags today),
# so this file grants the node role as a whole for now — which is still strictly better
# than the anonymous broker it replaces.
user econ-node
topic write econ/telemetry/#
topic write econ/status/#
topic read econ/commands/#

# The failsafe gateway additionally needs to SEE commands to detect engine liveness, and
# to publish its own setbacks when the engine goes silent.
user econ-gateway
topic read econ/telemetry/#
topic read econ/status/#
topic readwrite econ/commands/#
